        <body>       
 
                <pb n="1"/>
            <p>Dr. B. Felsenthal&#44;<lb/>
                450 W. Randolph St.<lb/></p>
            <p>CHICAGO&#44; April 4. 1888.<lb/>
                &#91;Hebrew&#93;<lb/></p>
            <p>Dr. S. Morais&#44; Philadelphia.<lb/></p>
            <p>Dear friend and colleague&#58;&#45;<lb/></p>
            <p>I am really glad that I have an <sic>occassion</sic> to<lb/> write to you again.  A few days ago I received<lb/> by mail a copy of the &#91;Hebrew&#93; &#40;Part 2<hi rend="sup">nd</hi>&#41;&#44;<lb/> which was recently published by Eisig Gr&#228;ber&#44; Jaroslau.<lb/>  In an accompanying circular letter the publisher<lb/> said that the Americans who receive the book<lb/> &#91;Hebrew&#93;<lb/> Please inform me now how much I shall send you&#44;<lb/> and I will then remit the amount by Post Office Order.<lb/></p>
            <p>I embrace this opportunity to ask you for<lb/> some information.  About 3 years ago&#44; in 1885&#44;<lb/> there was published by the &#91;Hebrew&#93; a volume en&#45;<lb/>titled &#34;&#91;Hebrew&#93;&#34;.  This volume contains&#44; among other<lb/> writings&#44; several poems by the brothers Jacob and Emanuel<lb/> Frances&#59; one of them is a Hebrew cantata by Emanuel<lb/></p>
                
                <pb n="2"/>
            <p>Frances&#44; preceding which the author says&#44;<lb/> &#34;&#91;Hebrew&#93;&#34;<lb/> when I read this&#44; and since then&#44; I was wondering<lb/> what kind of a society this &#91;Hebrew&#93; was.  In the<lb/> &#91;Hebrew&#93;&#44; published last year by Eisig Gr&#228;ber&#44;<lb/> is a biography of the 2 poets Frances&#44; and the<lb/> biographer&#44; David Kahana&#44; when he speaks of the<lb/> fact that Eman. Frances wrote his cantata upon<lb/> the request of the &#91;Hebrew&#93;&#44; says in a foot note<lb/> that in Italian the society was called &#91;Hebrew&#93;.  What kind of<lb/> a society was this &#91;Hebrew&#93;&#63;  Was it a social club&#44; or<lb/> a literary club&#44; or any other kind of society&#44; upon whose<lb/> request E. Fr. wrote his poem&#63;  What is the meaning of<lb/> &#34;&#91;Hebrew&#93;&#34;&#44; resp. of &#34;&#91;Hebrew&#93;&#34;&#63;<lb/></p>
            <p>In the April <hi rend="underline">Menorah</hi> you may probably<lb/> have noticed an article headed&#58; &#34;How old is<lb/> &#34;Jehova&#34;&#63;&#34; let me confess that I perpetrated<lb/> this article.<lb/></p>
            <p>In regard to the &#34;Jewish Theological<lb/> Seminary&#34; in New York permit me to express one<lb/> wish.  See to it&#44; my dear and venerated Sir&#44;<lb/> that the seminary does not degenerate into a mere<lb/></p>
                
                <pb n="3"/>
            <p>business college where Jewish boys are trained for<lb/> the Rabbi&#45;business&#59; but let it be the endeavor of<lb/> teachers and officers that the Seminary may<lb/> become a true institution of Jewish learning&#59;&#45;&#45;<lb/> an institution where &#91;Hebrew&#93; is taught&#59;&#45;&#45;an institution<lb/> where thoroughness and solidity of learning is aimed<lb/> at&#59; &#38;c. Not by the words &#34;reform&#44;&#34; or &#34;orthodox&#44;&#34;<lb/> or similar ones&#44; should such an institution be chracter&#45;<lb/>ized&#44; but by other adjectives.  A <hi rend="underline">good</hi> college<lb/> is one where something is <hi rend="underline">learned</hi>&#44; where the graduate&#44;<lb/> if not a &#34;&#91;Hebrew&#93;&#34;&#44; is at least a &#34;&#91;Hebrew&#93;&#34;&#44; a &#34;&#91;Hebrew&#93;&#34;.  A<lb/> not&#45;good college is one where nothing is learned<lb/> except external and really unprofitable things&#44;&#45;&#45;<lb/> no&#44; I am mistaken&#59; I should not have said<lb/> &#34;unprofitable&#34;&#44; I should have said &#34;profitable&#34;<lb/> things&#44; as f. i. the art of declamation&#44; &#38;c. &#38;c.<lb/></p>
                
                <pb n="4"/>
            <p>But I must close.  If I should have<lb/> said too much&#44; then &#91;Hebrew&#93;&#33;<lb/>
                Hoping soon to be honored by an<lb/> answer from you.<lb/>
                I am&#44; dear and venerated friend&#44;<lb/>
                Yours very truly<lb/>
                B. Felsenthal<lb/></p>
            </body>
